The VTP had predicted losses of just under 300,000 passengers a year as a result of the ban.

Meanwhile, UNESCO's president of the Italian National Commission was reportedly appalled by the decision, claiming that the public interest should take precedent over cruise ships.

Last year, the number of cruise ships sailing through Venice was capped at 708, compared to 809 in 2012.

